04744nam a22006855i 9780226583525DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018009198  a9780226583525  a(DE-B1597)523189  a(OCoLC)1059124995  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aR487b.L46 2018 4aR487b.L46 2019 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a615.88223  aLC 17005qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90626:7741 aLeong, Elaine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRecipes and Everyday Knowledge :bMedicine, Science, and the Household in Early Modern England /cElaine Leong. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b19 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Recipes, Households, and Everyday Knowledge -- tChapter 1. Making Recipe Books in Early Modern England: Material Practices and the Social Production of Knowledge -- tChapter 2. Managing Health and Household from Afar -- tChapter 3. Collecting Recipes Step- by- Step -- tChapter 4. Recipe Trials in the Early Modern Household -- tChapter 5. Writing the Family Archive: Recipes and the Paperwork of Kinship -- tChapter 6. Recipes for Sale: Intersections between Manuscript and Print Cultures -- tConclusion: Recipes Beyond the Household -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcross early modern Europe, men and women from all ranks gathered medical, culinary, and food preservation recipes from family and friends, experts and practitioners, and a wide array of printed materials. Recipes were tested, assessed, and modified by teams of householders, including masters and servants, husbands and wives, mothers and daughters, and fathers and sons. This much-sought know-how was written into notebooks of various shapes and sizes forming “treasuries for health,” each personalized to suit the whims and needs of individual communities. In Recipes and Everyday Knowledge, Elaine Leong situates recipe knowledge and practices among larger questions of gender and cultural history, the history of the printed word, and the history of science, medicine, and technology. The production of recipes and recipe books, she argues, were at the heart of "idian investigations of the natural world or “household science”. She shows how English homes acted as vibrant spaces for knowledge making and transmission, and explores how recipe trials allowed householders to gain deeper understandings of sickness and health, of the human body, and of natural and human-built processes. By recovering this story, Leong extends the parameters of natural inquiry and productively widens the cast of historical characters participating in and contributing to early modern science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFormulas, recipes, etczEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aFormulas, recipes, etc.zEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aHome economicszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aMedicine, PopularxHistoryy17th century. 0aNote-takingxHistoryy17th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aeveryday knowledge.  agender and science.  ahistory of experimentation.  ahistory of knowledge.  ahistory of medicine.  ahistory of science.  ahousehold science.  amanuscript and print cultures.  arecipes.  asocial knowledge.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022658349540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226583525423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226583525/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Ch